nodes.body: I'm really confused about these test failures, these tests don't have any local hypotheses and so therefore `compareHyp` should just not be running on them pretty much at all.

Pull request successfully merged into master.

Build succeeded:
  * [Build](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/7870398122/job/21471492489)
  * [Check all files imported](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/7870398122/job/21471491760)
  * [Lint style](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/7870398122/job/21471492264)

I'd like to run the defeq checks first as I think it's probably faster than just running `norm_num`, but it's actually not the easiest as it seems `MetaM` is not a monad that does exceptions. Is there another way to do it easily? Maybe just refactoring this defeq check into some method easily and running `orElse` on it?
I do the defeq check that was also deleted earlier for some matching or something of the like, so it's no longer needed here
Can you remove it from the docstring?

Another way around the bug here is to use
```suggestion
    let .defEq _  isDefEqQ (u := u.succ.succ)   | return .none
```
up to you which you prefer
I think your version is better after all, since my initial guess of the right universe was wrong!
It's annoying having to deal with universes so explicitly, and also having to deal with all the implicit parameters... oh well

```suggestion
  have e' : Q(Prop) := ldecl.type
  have p : Q($e') := .fvar ldecl.fvarId
```
then you can drop the `p`s below
it'd be nice if there was an inbuilt `Qq` way to do this, it feels a little type-unsafe
